---
import CalculatorLayout from '@layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro';
import { NetWorthCalc } from '@components/calculators/NetWorthCalc';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is net worth and why does it matter?',
    answer:
      'Net worth is the total value of everything you own (assets) minus everything you owe (liabilities). It\'s the single best number for tracking your overall financial health. Unlike income, which shows how much money flows in, net worth shows how much wealth you\'ve actually built. Tracking it regularly helps you see if you\'re moving in the right direction.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What counts as an asset?',
    answer:
      'Assets include anything of value you own: cash and savings accounts, investment accounts (401k, IRA, brokerage), real estate (your home\'s market value), vehicles, business equity, and valuable personal property. For this calculator, focus on significant assets — skip small items like furniture unless they have meaningful resale value.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is a good debt-to-asset ratio?',
    answer:
      'A debt-to-asset ratio below 50% is generally considered healthy — it means you own more than you owe. Below 30% is excellent. However, context matters: a 70% ratio can be normal for someone who recently bought a home with a mortgage. The key is trending downward over time as you pay off debts and build assets.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How often should I calculate my net worth?',
    answer:
      'Monthly or quarterly is ideal. Checking too frequently can cause stress from short-term market fluctuations, while checking too rarely means you miss trends. Pick a consistent schedule — many people track on the first of each month. The trend matters more than any single number.',
  },
];

const relatedCalculators = [
  {
    name: 'FIRE Calculator',
    description: 'Plan your path to financial independence based on your net worth and savings rate',
    href: '/personal-finance/fire-calculator',
    category: 'Personal Finance',
  },
  {
    name: 'Emergency Fund Calculator',
    description: 'Make sure you have enough liquid assets for emergencies',
    href: '/personal-finance/emergency-fund-calculator',
    category: 'Personal Finance',
  },
  {
    name: 'Debt Payoff Calculator',
    description: 'Create a plan to reduce your liabilities faster',
    href: '/personal-finance/debt-payoff-calculator',
    category: 'Personal Finance',
  },
  {
    name: 'Savings Goal Calculator',
    description: 'Plan monthly savings to grow your assets toward a specific target',
    href: '/personal-finance/savings-goal-calculator',
    category: 'Personal Finance',
  },
];
---

<CalculatorLayout
  title="Net Worth Calculator - Track Assets & Liabilities | CalcFalcon"
  description="Calculate your net worth by tracking all assets and liabilities. See asset allocation, debt-to-asset ratio, and projected growth. Free net worth calculator with charts."
  calculatorName="Net Worth Calculator"
  category="Personal Finance"
  categorySlug="personal-finance"
  slug="net-worth-calculator"
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedCalculators={relatedCalculators}
  ogImage="/og-images/net-worth.png"
>
  <Fragment slot="intro">
    <section class="mb-8">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>Net Worth: The One Number That Tells Your Whole Financial Story</h2>
        <p>Your net worth is the difference between what you own and what you owe — total assets minus total liabilities. It is the single most comprehensive measure of your financial health because it captures everything: savings, investments, property, debts, and loans in one number. Income tells you how much money flows through your hands; net worth tells you how much you have actually kept.</p>
        <p>For freelancers and independent workers, tracking net worth is particularly important because income variability can make monthly cash flow a misleading indicator. A freelancer who earns $15,000 one month and $3,000 the next might panic during the lean month, but if their net worth is steadily climbing, they are on a solid financial trajectory. Regular net worth snapshots reveal the long-term trend that monthly income numbers obscure.</p>
        <h3>What This Calculator Tracks</h3>
        <p>Add your assets by category — cash, investments, real estate, vehicles, and other valuables — and your liabilities by type — mortgage, student loans, credit cards, auto loans, and other debts. The calculator computes your total net worth, shows asset allocation in a donut chart, and calculates your debt-to-asset ratio. In Advanced mode, you can add growth rates and contribution amounts to project your net worth forward over multiple years.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <NetWorthCalc client:visible />
  <Fragment slot="content">
    <section class="mb-10">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>How to Use the Net Worth Calculator</h2>
        <p>Add all your assets and liabilities to get a clear picture of your financial position. The calculator shows your total net worth, asset allocation, and debt-to-asset ratio.</p>
        <h3>Quick Mode</h3>
        <p>Enter your assets with their current values and categories, plus all outstanding debts. You'll see your net worth, a donut chart of asset allocation, and breakdowns of both sides of your balance sheet.</p>
        <h3>Advanced Mode</h3>
        <p>Add growth rates to each asset and interest rates to liabilities for a multi-year net worth projection. Set annual contributions to investment accounts to see how your net worth could grow over time with consistent saving and compounding returns.</p>
        <h3>Why Track Net Worth?</h3>
        <p>Income tells you how much money comes in, but net worth tells you how much wealth you've actually built. It accounts for debt, spending habits, and investment growth in a single number. For freelancers and self-employed workers, tracking net worth is especially important since income can be irregular — the trend of your net worth over time is the truest measure of financial progress.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="deep-dive">
    <section class="mb-10">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <h2>Average Net Worth by Age in the United States</h2>
        <p>The following benchmarks come from the Federal Reserve's Survey of Consumer Finances. Median is more useful than average because a few ultra-wealthy individuals skew the average significantly upward.</p>
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Age Group</th><th>Median Net Worth</th><th>Average Net Worth</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Under 35</td><td>$39,000</td><td>$183,500</td></tr>
            <tr><td>35 - 44</td><td>$135,600</td><td>$549,600</td></tr>
            <tr><td>45 - 54</td><td>$247,200</td><td>$975,800</td></tr>
            <tr><td>55 - 64</td><td>$364,500</td><td>$1,566,900</td></tr>
            <tr><td>65 - 74</td><td>$410,000</td><td>$1,794,600</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p>If your net worth is above the median for your age group, you are doing better than half of American households. The gap between median and average reflects the extreme wealth concentration at the top.</p>
        <h2>The Five Components of Net Worth Growth</h2>
        <p><strong>1. Earning more.</strong> Higher income provides more raw material for wealth building. For freelancers, this means raising rates, specializing, or adding revenue streams. Income is the engine — but only if you convert it into savings rather than lifestyle inflation.</p>
        <p><strong>2. Spending less.</strong> Reducing expenses has the same mathematical effect as earning more, but it also lowers your FIRE number and the portfolio needed for financial independence. Every dollar not spent is a dollar that can compound.</p>
        <p><strong>3. Investing consistently.</strong> Regular contributions to investment accounts — regardless of market conditions — take advantage of dollar-cost averaging and ensure you capture long-term market growth. Even small monthly contributions add up significantly over decades.</p>
        <p><strong>4. Reducing debt.</strong> Every debt payment increases your net worth twice: it reduces liabilities directly and eliminates future interest charges. Prioritize high-interest debt for the biggest impact.</p>
        <p><strong>5. Time and compounding.</strong> Given enough time, compound returns do most of the heavy lifting. A $500 monthly investment at 7 percent return grows to $122,000 in 10 years, $265,000 in 15 years, and $525,000 in 20 years. The last five years contribute more than the first ten combined.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>
</CalculatorLayout>
